   <titles>
      <title>Linear Motion</title>
      <plain.title>Linear Motion</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>A particle moves linearly If it moves straight and with constant speed, and so we call its motion a  linear motion. Vectors are ideally suited to describe such motions. We just need to learn how to interpret the following definition:</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_LinearMotion">
               <caption>Linear Motion</caption>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The linear motion through <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{a}</latex>
                        </math> with velocity vector <math>
                           <latex>\mathbf{v}</latex>
                        </math> is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <para align="center">
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>\mathbf{l}(t)\ =\ \mathbf{a} + t\cdot \mathbf{v}</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Read this as: ‘ell of <math>
                                       <latex>t</latex>
                                    </math> equals a plus t times v’</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>, with <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>t\in \RNr</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Read this as: ‘t in R’, which means: <math>
                                       <latex>t</latex>
                                    </math> is a number in <math>
                                       <latex>\RNr</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>linear</term>
                        <term>motion</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>A motion of a particle whose location at time <math>
                                    <latex>t</latex>
                                 </math> has position vector <math>
                                    <latex>\mathbf{l}(t)\ =\ \mathbf{a} + t\cdot \mathbf{v}</latex>
                                 </math>. – Click to see to the definition.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>velocity vector</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Click to see the definition of the velocity vector of a linear motion.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The variable <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> is called the time parameter for the motion, and the above equation is the parametric equation for the given linear motion.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>How does vector expression in the above definition describe a motion? We interpret the variable <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> as time and the vector <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{l}(t)</latex>
                  </math> as the <subordinate>
                     <hot>position vector</hot>
                     <companion>
                        <unit.ref unitId="LinearMotion_Explntn"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>An explanation of the concept of a linear motion</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </companion>
                  </subordinate> of a moving particle at time <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math>. So, at time <math>
                     <latex>t=0</latex>
                  </math>, the particle is at <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{a}</latex>
                  </math>; at time <math>
                     <latex>t=1</latex>
                  </math>, the particle is at <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{v}</latex>
                  </math>; at time <math>
                     <latex>t=2</latex>
                  </math>, the particle is at <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{a} + 2\cdot \mathbf{v}</latex>
                  </math>, etc. In particular, during the time interval <math>
                     <latex>[0,1]</latex>
                  </math>, the particle has been displaced by the vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math>. This is why we call <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{v}</latex>
                  </math> the velocity vector of the motion.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
